2500|$|In {{a memoir}} written for Robert Goffin between 1943 and 1944, Armstrong states, [...] "All <b>white</b> <b>folks</b> call me Louie," [...] {{suggesting}} that he himself did not. That said, Armstrong was registered as [...] "Lewie" [...] for the 1920 U.S. Census. On various live records he's called [...] "Louie" [...] on stage, such as on the 1952 [...] "Can Anyone Explain?" [...] from the live album In Scandinavia vol.1. [...] "Lewie" [...] is the French pronunciation of [...] "Louis" [...] and is commonly used in Louisiana.|$|E
50|$|Conforth {{believes}} that Gellert's large collection, which comprises predominantly blues and devotional songs, {{is of great}} historical importance nevertheless. According to Conforth, Gellert {{had no interest in}} politics himself. Nor was he interested in <b>white</b> <b>folk</b> music, which he despised. A strikingly handsome man, who was, especially when young, very attractive to women, Gellert had originally wanted to become a Broadway actor.|$|R
