2500|$|Early blues {{frequently}} {{took the}} form of a loose narrative. African-American singers voiced his or her [...] "personal woes in a world of harsh reality: a lost love, the cruelty of police officers, oppression at the hands of <b>white</b> <b>folk,</b> [...] hard times". This melancholy has led to the suggestion of an Igbo origin for blues because of the reputation the Igbo had throughout plantations in the Americas for their melancholic music and outlook on life when they were enslaved.|$|R
